Paul -

Well, I don&#39;t know how it got left out, but the &#39;size&#39; attribute was 
missing from the &#39;ctml_writer.py&#39; module that ct2ctml uses.  So 
although Cantera supports using the size parameter for surface species, 
it would have to be added by hand to the CTML file, since it is not 
understood in the CTI file.  This has now been fixed, so you can check 
out from CVS the latest version of ctml_writer.py 
(&#39;Cantera/python/ctml_writer.py&#39; in the repository) and simply replace 
the version you have in your Cantera Python package with the new 
version.  I haven&#39;t had need to use the &#39;size&#39; parameter, and I guess 
no one else has either until now!

Steven - your suggested work-around might work, but also might give 
undesired behavior. The &#39;ads(S)&#39; species would contain twice the number 
of atoms as S, but since its &#39;size&#39; is 1, the site density would be the 
same as S.  This would affect the way the conversion from coverage to 
surface concentration is done.

I have found that it is all too easy to write a surface reaction that 
does not conserve surface sites, and then strange things start to 
happen.  As an added check to help Cantera flag reactions that don&#39;t 
conserve sites, I often define an &#39;element&#39; corresponding to each site 
type.  For example, a CTI file might look like this:

---------------------------
element(&#39;&#39;surf_site&#39;)
...
species(name = &#39;S&#39;, atoms = &#39;surf_site:1&#39;, ...)

species(name = &#39;ads(S)&#39;, atoms = &#39;surf_site:2&#39;, size = 2, ...)
---------------------------

By declaring that ads(S) contains 2 &#39;atoms&#39; of &#39;surf_site&#39;, Cantera 
will be able to check any reaction containing it for site conservation. 
  The size parameter must also be supplied to do concentration &lt;-&gt; 
coverage conversion correctly.

An &#39;element&#39; declaration with no atomic weight is assigned a very small 
but non-zero atomic weight, to avoid problems with dividing by zero in 
mass/mole conversion. You can use this to define anything you want to 
conserve in a reaction (sites, spin, ...), without measurably affecting 
molecular weights.
If species are defined that contain only these &#39;virtual&#39; elements, 
corresponding to an empty site, then mass fractions for these will be 
nearly zero, but it is better to describe surface species in molar, not 
mass, terms anyway.

Dave



